 File format parsers (Virgil)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Images:   PNG  JPG  GIF  SVG  WEBP  BMP  ICO
Audio:    MP3  M4A  WAV  AAC  FLAC  OGG
Video:    MP4  MKV  WEBM  AVI
Other:    GPX  MIDI

Status:
  [x] MP3  — parser + dumper done (ID3v2/v1, MPEG frame, Xing/LAME)
  [x] PNG  — parser + dumper done
  [x] GIF  — parser + dumper done
  [ ] MP3 audio decoding — Layer III (see mp3/notes.md for full roadmap)
  [ ] WAV  — straightforward RIFF chunk parser; needed for raw PCM looping
  [ ] MIDI — event-level parser; needed for tab/score sync and MIDI capture
  [ ] FLAC — streaminfo + frame headers; needed for lossless source support

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Resonate — EWMA resonator bank
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Reference: https://alexandrefrancois.org/Resonate/
Author: Alexandre François

Core idea:
  Each resonator tracks one frequency f using an Exponentially Weighted Moving
  Average (EWMA) of the complex signal e^(2πi·f·t) evaluated at each sample.
  Update per sample: Z[n] = α · Z[n-1] + (1-α) · x[n] · e^(-iφ[n])
  where α controls the time constant (bandwidth) and φ accumulates phase.
  Output: magnitude |Z[n]| and phase arg(Z[n]) at every sample — no buffering,
  no windowing, zero latency, only a multiply and an add per resonator per sample.
  Optionally: allow resonators to track a drifting frequency by monitoring
  instantaneous phase changes (frequency-adaptive mode).

Why it matters for RiffHound:
  - Zero-latency per-sample analysis vs. FFT's hop-size latency
  - No windowing artifacts; exact phase available at every sample
  - Trivially parallelizable (each resonator is independent)
  - Can replace FFT in chroma analyzer, onset detector, and spectrogram
  - Enables live-input analysis that FFT-hop-based methods cannot match

Candidate uses:

  1. Real-time chroma (replace chroma_goertzel.cpp)
     - 12 (or 36 for 3-octave) resonators tuned to chromatic pitches
     - Magnitude per pitch updated every sample → instantaneous chord snapshot
     - Phase available for onset-accurate beat alignment
     - Could feed chord display, key estimation, auto-accompaniment key locking

  2. Onset / beat detection from live input
     - Wideband resonator bank → track energy per band per sample
     - Detect sharp rises in magnitude → onsets with sample-accurate timing
     - Phase continuity break → note attack detection
     - Could replace or augment the Ellis DP tracker for live (non-file) input

  3. Pitch tracker for monophonic instruments (lead guitar, vocals, harmonica)
     - Sweep resonator bank across full pitch range (e.g. MIDI 36–84)
     - Dominant resonator = fundamental pitch
     - Track glides, bends, vibrato via adaptive frequency-tracking mode
     - Feed into pitch-trace overlay on spectrogram / score display

  4. Key / scale detector for live input
     - 12 resonators → normalize magnitude vector → correlate with major/minor
       templates → real-time key confidence updated per sample
     - Could drive auto-transposition of chord display and backing tracks

  5. Time-stretch / pitch-shift engine
     - Resonate can synthesize audio from tracked components
     - Modify phase accumulation rate → time-stretch without windowing artifacts
     - Shift resonator frequencies → pitch-shift without resampling
     - Could replace or complement WSOLA in the beatmapper for loop playback

  6. Spectrogram replacement
     - Arbitrary frequency scale (log, mel, guitar, piano) with no FFT overhead
     - Update display every N samples (e.g. N=64) for smooth scrolling
     - Better frequency resolution at low end than FFT with same window size

  Implementation notes:
  - Core resonator loop is ~5 lines of C; vectorizes trivially with SIMD
  - Frequency set is fixed at init; can change α to tune bandwidth per resonator
  - Phase must be accumulated carefully (use double or Kahan sum) to avoid drift
  - For chromatic use: tune to equal temperament, A4=440, all 12 pitch classes
    across 3–5 octaves; sum octave bins for chroma reduction
  - Adaptive mode: compare arg(Z[n]) - arg(Z[n-1]) to expected dφ; nudge f

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Looping / playback application
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Goal: a low-latency loop station + smart jam companion that runs without a
 central display, controlled by voice, footswitches, and MIDI.

 Core loop engine:
  - Load audio file → decode to PCM (use Virgil MP3/WAV parsers or miniaudio)
  - Define loop points from beatmap annotations (beat-aligned boundaries)
  - Cross-fade at loop boundaries; configurable fade length
  - Independent pitch-shift and time-stretch (WSOLA or Resonate synthesis)
  - Multi-loop: stack multiple independent looping regions with separate
    pitch/speed controls (e.g. drum loop + chord loop + bass loop)
  - Sync mode: slave all loops to a master tempo; beat-quantized start/stop

 Voice control (see transcripts.txt for real interaction examples):
  - "drums at 115"               → set tempo, start drum loop
  - "something funky"            → select style parameter
  - "bass in E, basic blues"     → load/generate bass in key E, 12-bar pattern
  - "too busy / make it simpler" → reduce density parameter
  - "bring in the chords"        → unmute chord loop
  - "let's go down to 110"       → ramp tempo
  - Architecture: footswitch activates mic → Whisper (Python) → intent parser
    → command dispatcher → loop engine

 Sections / arrangement:
  - Named sections from beatmap (verse, chorus, bridge, solo, etc.)
  - Jump to section by voice: "go to the chorus"
  - Repeat N times, then auto-advance
  - Fade out / end

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 AI models — Python subprocess integration
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Architecture: beatmapper or jam buddy spawns a Python sidecar process.
 Communication: named pipe or Unix socket, binary frames or newline-delimited
 JSON. Audio sent as raw f32 PCM chunks; results returned as structured data.

 Model                  | Capability                        | RiffHound use
 -----------------------|-----------------------------------|---------------------------
 Whisper (OpenAI)       | Speech → text, very robust        | Voice command recognition;
                        |                                   | lyric transcription from
                        |                                   | audio for lyricmap
 Demucs (Meta)          | Source separation: separate       | Isolate drums/bass/guitar/
                        | drums, bass, vocals, guitar       | vocals; feed stems into
                        | from a mixed recording            | beat detector or chroma
 Basic Pitch (Spotify)  | Audio → MIDI (polyphonic)         | Auto-tab; feed MIDI into
                        |                                   | chord display; score gen
 CREPE                  | Monophonic pitch tracking         | Pitch trace for vocals /
                        |                                   | lead guitar overlay on
                        |                                   | spectrogram
 MusicGen (Meta)        | Text/audio conditioned music      | Generate backing tracks
                        | generation                        | from voice description:
                        |                                   | "give me a funky bassline"
 madmom / BeatNet       | Pre-trained beat + downbeat       | Supplement C++ Ellis DP;
                        | tracker (RNN-based)               | better on complex rhythms
 essentia (MTG)         | Key, tempo, danceability,         | Library tagging pipeline;
                        | tonal/rhythmic descriptors        | song similarity search
 chord recognition      | Real-time chord from audio        | Drive chord display and
 (crema, autochord)     | (CNN/CRF models)                  | auto-accompaniment changes
 AudioCraft / Stable    | Generative music                  | On-demand jam companion
 Audio                  |                                   | track synthesis
 YAMNet / VGGish        | Audio event classification        | Detect instrument, genre,
                        |                                   | or percussive event type

 Priority for first integration:
  1. Whisper — highest leverage; voice control is core UX
  2. Demucs — beat detector works much better on isolated drum stem
  3. madmom — drop-in beat tracker that actually installs (see notes.txt);
     use Python 3.10+ to avoid Cython/madmom build failures on 3.9
  4. Basic Pitch — auto-tab pipeline from any audio file
  5. chord recognition — real-time key/chord for live chroma display

 Notes on madmom / BeatNet install failure (from notes.txt):
  The issue is Python 3.9 + old Cython. Solution:
    brew install pyenv
    pyenv install 3.11.x
    pyenv local 3.11.x
    pip install madmom  # builds cleanly on 3.11

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
 Songmap pipeline
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 Goal: `songmap <file.mp3>` → structured annotation file covering:
  - beatmap (beat times, tempo map, sections)
  - chord map (chord per beat or segment)
  - lyrics (aligned to beats via Whisper)
  - key / scale / mode
  - instrument separation (Demucs stems)
  - guitar tab (Basic Pitch MIDI → tab converter)
  - structural analysis (intro/verse/chorus/bridge/outro via essentia or CNN)
  - similarity fingerprint for library search

 Stages:
  1. Decode audio → PCM (miniaudio / Virgil MP3 parser)
  2. Beat detection: C++ Ellis DP (beatmapper) or madmom (Python)
  3. Source separation: Demucs (Python) → drum stem → refine beat detection
  4. Chroma + chord: Resonate bank or crema (Python)
  5. Lyrics: Whisper (Python) → align to beatmap
  6. MIDI transcription: Basic Pitch (Python) → guitar tab
  7. Structure: essentia or segment CNN (Python)
  8. Output: JSON/text annotation file consumed by beatmapper and jam buddy

